          "body": "Chapter 13 established Samson's identity with unusual solemnity: the angel of the LORD himself announces the Nazirite dedication from the womb, with explicit prohibitions of wine, strong drink, and contact with the dead (13:4–5, 14). Chapter 14 places Samson in the vineyards of Timnah (14:5) on his way to negotiate a Philistine marriage, then has him eat honey from a lion's corpse (14:8–9) and attend a seven-day *mishteh* (drinking feast, 14:10). Every element of the chapter presses against the Nazirite boundary. The honey from the carcass is almost certainly a corpse-defilement violation (Numbers 6:6–7); the feast context implies wine; the marriage itself crosses covenant lines. The narrator records these without editorial pause, which is itself the judgment: the reader who knows the Nazirite law hears what the narrator does not say. Samson is called to a high consecration and lives as if the call makes no demands."
