        "excerpt": "However, his father and mother did not know that it was of the LORD, for He was seeking an occasion against the Philistines.",
        "body": "The opening four verses establish the chapter's governing paradox immediately. Samson sees, desires, and demands — no courtship, no prayer, no parental consultation beyond a notification. His rationale ('she looks good to me,' 14:3) uses the precise Hebrew phrase (*yashar b'einai*, 'right/straight in my eyes') that the book of Judges reserves for its most pointed theological indictment: Judges 17:6 and 21:25 use identical language to summarize an entire generation's anarchic self-determination. The reader schooled in Judges' rhetoric hears the alarm.\n\nAnd then the narrator inserts verse 4. The same demand — which Samson's parents rightly identify as a violation of the Mosaic prohibition on intermarriage with Canaanite peoples (Deuteronomy 7:3–4, which extends by analogy to Philistines) — is disclosed as instrumentally 'of the LORD.' This is not the narrator domesticating sin or excusing covenant violation. The text does not say God prescribed the marriage; it says God was working through the circumstances the marriage set in motion. The distinction is crucial. Reformed theologians following Calvin distinguish between God's *decretive will* (what He sovereignly ordains to come to pass) and His *preceptive will* (what He commands of His creatures morally). Samson violates the preceptive will — he does what is right in his own eyes, crossing a clear covenant boundary. God uses that violation in His decretive will — working through it to engineer the conflict that begins Israel's deliverance from Philistine domination.\n\nD. A. Carson's treatment of God's sovereignty and evil (*How Long, O Lord?*, 1990) is relevant here: God can ordain circumstances that involve human sin without being the author of that sin or approving it. The responsibility for Samson's choice is entirely Samson's. The providential repurposing of that choice is entirely God's. Both are simultaneously true, and the narrator holds them without flinching.\n\nThe chapter's opening, then, is not an excuse for Samson but a warning against a particular interpretive error: concluding that because God uses a choice, God endorses it. The prosperity and apparent productivity of a sinful decision does not retroactively make the decision righteous.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yashar b'einai* (right/straight in my eyes, vv.3, 7) — the same construction as the book's closing verdict (21:25). *Taanah* (occasion, v.4) — a pretext or opportunity for conflict; the word implies God is the active agent engineering the circumstance. *Mashal* (ruling, v.4) — the same verb used of legitimate governance; its use for Philistine domination over Israel is a sustained implicit accusation throughout the Samson cycle."
